<subSubSection box="[151,1360,973,1000]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,973,2008]" box="[151,1360,973,1000]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,973,999]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Etymology</emphasis>
. The genus name refers to the remarkable male pygidium of the 
<typeStatus box="[1005,1053,974,1000]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">type</typeStatus>
species, gender masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="577" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,973,2008]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1009,1035]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This new genus is distinguished from the other American genera by the following combination of male characters: rostrum (
<figureCitation box="[485,628,1045,1072]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 1, 3, 5</figureCitation>
) convex dorsally at prorostral level in side view, ventral surface with two elongate longitudinal and coarsely punctate sulci (
<figureCitation box="[770,880,1081,1108]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
); pronotum campaniform in dorsal view, slightly constricted before apex, slightly bisinuate with rounded median projection toward scutellum, without basal flange (
<figureCitation box="[159,270,1153,1179]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 1–4</figureCitation>
); scutellum glabrous and depressed in middle; hind wings with small radial window; hypomeral lobes divided by median suture and distinctly exposed sternellum; meso- and metatibiae mucronate; pygidium (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 10, 11</figureCitation>
) of the incomplete apionine 
<typeStatus box="[508,560,1226,1252]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">type</typeStatus>
; basal piece fused with tegminal plate (
<figureCitation box="[1001,1084,1225,1251]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="578" pageId="2" pageNumber="577" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,973,2008]" box="[199,586,1261,1288]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,409,1261,1287]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Description. Size:</emphasis>
<quantity box="[416,582,1261,1288]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="2" pageNumber="577" unit="mm" value="1.95" valueMax="2.2" valueMin="1.7">1.70–2.20 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,973,2008]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,306,1297,1323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Vestiture</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[322,428,1297,1323]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
) in general conspicuous, with sparse and homogeneous off-white scales; meta- and mesorostrum with scales reduced, absent on prorostrum; scales of head, thorax and coxae similar in size; with centripetal vestiture on pronotum, except in posterior region where scales are perpendicular to posterior margin; denser on sides of pro-, meso- and metasternum; elytral interstriae with two or three irregular rows of scales; legs with very sparse scales; uniform on abdominal ventrites; pygidium with centripetal vestiture (
<figureCitation box="[1010,1093,1441,1467]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,973,2008]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,305,1477,1503]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Rostrum</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[321,427,1477,1503]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 1–7</figureCitation>
) cylindrical, longer than pronotum along midline; in lateral view curved, more convex at prorostral level (
<figureCitation box="[337,444,1513,1540]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 1–5</figureCitation>
); surface polished and finely punctate. Males with ventral surface of rostrum with longitudinal sulci punctate, squamous (
<figureCitation box="[532,639,1549,1576]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,973,2008]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,263,1585,1611]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[278,384,1585,1611]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 1–4</figureCitation>
) with frons slightly sloped; medially glabrous with marginal scales smaller than scales around eyes; subocular keel developed, not extending to posterior margin of eyes; area between subocular keels microreticulate, impunctate. Eyes round, convex (
<figureCitation box="[633,773,1657,1684]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 1–5, 7</figureCitation>
). Antennae (
<figureCitation box="[920,988,1657,1684]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) inserted at basal 0.24-0.28 of rostrum length in both sexes; scape 0.65-0.90 times mesorostral width, 4.33-5.80 times as long as wide, as long as club; pedicel longer than wide, as long as desmomeres 1+2; desmomeres 2–5 times as long as wide, desmomere 6 nearly as long as wide, subconical; club oblong and compact, 2 times as long as wide, as long as last five desmomeres; sutures marked.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,973,2008]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,970]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="578" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,288,1837,1863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Thorax</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[303,410,1837,1863]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="577">Figs. 1–4</figureCitation>
). Pronotum campaniform in dorsal view, transverse, slightly constricted before apex, about 0.65-0.70 times as long as wide, base 1.40-1.60 times apical width, slightly bisinuate with rounded median projection toward scutellum, without basal flange; outline in lateral view slightly convex medially; pronotal disc with sub-basal fovea slightly depressed; punctures covered by scales. Procoxae contiguous, hypomeral lobes divided by median suture with sternellum distinctly exposed. Mesocoxa separated, mesosternal apophysis 1/3 as wide as mesocoxae, truncate at apex. Metacoxa transverse, metasternum narrowed, declivous anteriorly to metacoxa. Mesofemora slightly more robust than pro- and metafemora. Meso- and metatibiae mucronate. All tarsomeres 1 longer than wide, tarsomeres 2 wider than long, tarsomeres 3 bilobed; onychium 2.5 to 3.0 times longer than wide, surpassing lobes of tarsomere 3 by ca. 1/5 length of onychium. Tarsal claws toothed at base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">
Elytral length 1.40-1.80 times distance between humeri, convex (lateral view, 
<figureCitation box="[1060,1166,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Figs. 1–4</figureCitation>
); humeri salient, formed by glabrous basal intumescences of interstriae 6; longitudinal striae present, strongly punctate apically, at apex joining 1+9, 2, 3+4, 5+6, 7+8; interstriae 7 and 9 each with one specialized seta in apical half. Apical margin of epipleura conspicuously extended. Macropterous, hind wings with small radial window (
<figureCitation box="[1111,1180,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,438,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Ventrite 1 the most elongated, impressed at disk; ventrite 2 longer than ventrites 3+4; ventrites 3 and 4 narrow; pygidium of incomplete apionine 
<typeStatus box="[646,694,475,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">type</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[709,844,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Figs. 10, 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,556,510,537]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Male terminalia and genitalia.</emphasis>
Ninth sternite (spiculum gastrale) Y-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[1054,1136,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Penis (
<figureCitation box="[1229,1308,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) impressed and curved; pedon with apical plate straight in lateral view, rounded apically in dorsal view; tectum slender and with clear margins. Tegmen (
<figureCitation box="[426,509,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) with tegminal plate fused to basal piece; suprafenestral plate with macrochaetae posterior to each fenestra; fenestrae and linea arquata visible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,404,654,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Spiculum ventrale elongate and straight, apical plate membranous and setiferous (
<figureCitation box="[1339,1423,654,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor (
<figureCitation box="[288,372,691,718]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), coxite long with microchaetae; styli subcylindrical and with macrochaetae. Spermatheca Cshaped (
<figureCitation box="[244,327,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,186,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[189,1398,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: hind wing (9); male pygidium, dorsal view (10) and lateral view (11); spiculum gastrale (12); penis, dorsal view (13); tegmen, dorsal view (14); spiculum, ventral view (15); coxite and styli (16); spermatheca (17)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629481/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
), lacking nodulus or ramus; cornu and corpus evident.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,438,762,788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Sexual dimorphism.</emphasis>
Female differing from male in having longer and wider body; rostrum narrower and more slender (
<figureCitation box="[247,356,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Figs. 2, 4</figureCitation>
); and ventral surface at mesorostral level without ventral sulci (
<figureCitation box="[1069,1176,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,194,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Pygidiapion zeppelinii sp. n.: holotype male (1) and paratype female in lateral view (2); SEM micrographs of male (3) and female (4) in lateral view, head (5) and rostrum of male (6); head (7) and rostrum of female (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629477/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Figs. 7, 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,404,834,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="578">Included species.</emphasis>
